After taking a break for half a day, I came back to the project to take another crack at it, and I seem to have got things working (to a roughly acceptable degree).

***What I did:***

- First of all, I changed from using a ```Task``` to using a ```Thread```.
- Secondly, before I create the thread, I store the value of ```Thread.CurrentThread```.
- Then, inside of the newly created *game loop thread*, I have a ```while (Running)``` loop. Each time the loop is entered, I call the game&#39;s update and render functions, as well as the ```GLControl```&#39;s ```SwapBuffers()``` function from within a call to: ```Dispatcher.FromThread(mainThread).Invoke(( ) =&gt; { ... });```

This runs those functions from the main thread. I&#39;m not sure exactly what&#39;s going on behind the scenes to make this work, and I&#39;m almost certain that there&#39;s a better way to do this, but... it does work perfectly for my needs.

Here is the game loop thread code, in the hopes that this helps someone in the future (and PLEASE, if this is terrible code (and I bet it is), tell me why, and how it can be improved)

***Game loop thread code:***
```
Thread mainThread = Thread.CurrentThread;
new Thread(() =&gt;
{
    Dispatcher.FromThread(mainThread).Invoke(() =&gt;
    {
        Debug.LogInfo(&quot;Game loop thread started!&quot;, EditorTextColour.Green);
    });
                    
    while (Running)
    {
        if (IsInitialized)
        {
            Dispatcher.FromThread(mainThread).Invoke(() =&gt;
            {
                Update();
                Render();
                if (Embedded)
                {
                    EmbeddedControl.SwapBuffers();
                }
            });
        }
        Thread.Sleep(200); // TODO: Tune this using actual timing values!!
    }
}).Start();
```

***Result:***

The engine runs the game, tells it that it&#39;s embedded in an editor, and calls the game&#39;s ```Run()``` function. The game notices it&#39;s embedded, and chooses not to create a window, instead starting the code shown above (after calling an ```Initialize()``` function to ensure any needed values can be set before using them). The *game loop thread* calls the game&#39;s ```Update()``` and ```Render()``` functions **from the main thread, via the ```Dispatcher```**, and sleeps after each loop. Et Voil&#225;, we have a game running inside its very own WPF editor! Pretty neat, for a learning exercise!

